(1.1 VMS Security \(1984-1994\)) show newline
(----------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(DEC was a family. This was merely one specialty.) show newline
() show newline
(The Security Project Team was Derrell Piper, Mark Pilant, Andy) show newline
(Goldstein. TCSEC C2/B1 certification on VAX/VMS and Alpha VMS. VMS 6.0.) show newline
() show newline
(What we built:) show newline
() show newline
(  * $CHKPRO - the privilege checking gate, the single point where all privilege decisions were made) show newline
(  * The entire auditing subsystem \(final form\), comprehensive privilege and access logging) show newline
(  * C2/B1 certified security model \(Orange Book compliance, proven secure\)) show newline
() show newline
(Access: The security project team \(or anyone we designated\) were the) show newline
(only ones allowed in the kernel group's modules. Dave Cutler's team) show newline
(begrudgingly accepted this as a mandate from heaven \(Ken Olsen /) show newline
(Maynard\). We got in on a mandate. We stayed because the work was good.) show newline
() show newline
(Inheritance: When Cutler left for Microsoft, his modules were inherited.) show newline
(The privilege auditing 'rototill' required fluency in MACRO-32.) show newline
() show newline
(Text in the Library of Cyberspace is in the color of phosphor green, the) show newline
(color of VT100s and reflective of IBM green bar printouts. Not retro.) show newline
(Not nostalgia. Memory.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(1.2 The Road Not Taken) show newline
(----------------------) show newline
() show newline
(We all built VAX/VMS V6.0 and then we threw it away--literally tossing) show newline
(our green bar printouts of our respective subsystems into an empty cube) show newline
(on ZK03/4. The code of what could have been. The end of DEC.) show newline
() show newline
(They must have done something similar after Prism/Mica was cancelled,) show newline
(ahead of that fateful offer to Gates & Co. that gifted Microsoft) show newline
(dominance in COTS computing.) show newline
() show newline
(Prism/Mica was being designed for TCSEC B1. That's the legacy--the) show newline
(mindset, the trust model, and the codebase--that Gates was gifted in an) show newline
(offer they couldn't refuse.) show newline
() show newline
(Of all the people at DEC, Cutler--designer of the MicroVAX--could see) show newline
(the writing on the wall. The age of PCs had been born. Digital missed) show newline
(the train.) show newline
() show newline
(The weave predates the software. The people who understood trust) show newline
(architectures kept finding each other:) show newline
() show newline
(  * DEC -> Microsoft -> Cisco -> here) show newline
(  * Peter Lofgren was there. There's a photograph of that meeting floating around in PDP-10 space. He ended up at Cisco--our nexus.) show newline
() show newline
(The thread is unbroken. From the people who built it, through the people) show newline
(who maintained it, to the people who understood what was lost. And now) show newline
(into the code.) show newline
() show newline
(That's provenance you can't fake.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(1.3 Languages) show newline
(-------------) show newline
() show newline
(BLISS - Bill Wulf at CMU \(1969\) created BLISS as an expression language,) show newline
(not 'DEC's C'. Everything returns a value. Lisp in systems clothing.) show newline
() show newline
(MACRO-32 - VAX assembly with rich macros. The kernel was MACRO-32.) show newline
(Learned it from the privilege auditing rototill.) show newline
() show newline
(The VMS Runtime - Had a rich macro wrapper for BLISS. That macro system) show newline
(was a Lisp. We knew. That's why we used it.) show newline
() show newline
(A Lisper who fell in love with BLISS \(an expression language, like) show newline
(home\).) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(1.4 System Service Vocabulary) show newline
(-----------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(The VMS system service vocabulary provides the conceptual heritage for) show newline
(Cyberspace's security primitives.) show newline
() show newline
(The security subsystem was written exclusively in BLISS \(with MACRO-32) show newline
(fluency for reading the layers beneath\). Now it's Scheme.) show newline
() show newline
(Access check pattern:) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(    $CREATE_USER_PROFILE  >  builds encoded user security profile) show newline
(            v) show newline
(    $CHKPRO / $CHECK_ACCESS  >  evaluates access using profile + object protection) show newline
(            v) show newline
(    SS$_NORMAL / SS$_NOPRIV  >  grant or deny) show newline
() show newline
(Key item codes \(CHP$_*\):) show newline
() show newline
(  * CHP$_ACCESS > access-mask \(requested access type bitmask\)) show newline
(  * CHP$_PROT > protection \(SOGW protection mask\)) show newline
(  * CHP$_OWNER > owner \(object owner identifier\)) show newline
(  * CHP$_UIC > principal \(accessor's identity\)) show newline
(  * CHP$_PRIV > privileges \(privilege mask\)) show newline
(  * CHP$_ACL > acl \(access control list\)) show newline
(  * CHP$_FLAGS > flags \(check options: observe/alter\)) show newline
() show newline
(Flags: CHP$V_AUDIT > audit?, CHP$V_OBSERVE > read?, CHP$V_ALTER > write?) show newline
() show newline
(Return status: SS$_NORMAL > #t, SS$_NOPRIV > #f, SS$_ACCVIO > 'accvio,) show newline
(SS$_IVACL > 'invalid-acl) show newline
() show newline
(Impersonation \($PERSONA_*\): Used by DECdfs and distributed file services) show newline
(to act on behalf of remote clients without re-implementing access) show newline
(checks.) show newline
() show newline
($PERSONA was designed by the DEC Distributed File System group, not VMS) show newline
(Engineering.) show newline
() show newline
(The original $IMPERSONATION framework was authored by myself with Rich) show newline
(Bouchard. It was lost during the Mitnick incidents when Andy Goldstein) show newline
(and I decided we needed to rebuild our compiler chain from known good) show newline
(offsite backups - with Ken Thompson's 'Reflections on Trusting Trust') show newline
(fresh in our minds. In doing so, we lost a year of development during) show newline
(Alpha, including the original kernel threads implementation and the) show newline
($IMPERSONATION framework.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(1.5 Syntax Heritage) show newline
(-------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Dylan-style keyword arguments are a tribute to Apple Cambridge and MIT:) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(    \(translate text from: 'en to: 'fr\)) show newline
(    \(enroll-request name timeout: 30\)) show newline
() show newline
(Ada/Dylan/BLISS style - named parameters, self-documenting:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Ada: Open\(File => "data.txt", Mode => Read_Only\)) show newline
(  * Dylan: open\(file: "data.txt", mode: #"read"\)) show newline
(  * BLISS: OPEN\(FILE = 'data.txt', MODE = READONLY\)) show newline
() show newline
(Self syntax was weird. Smalltalk doesn't work for math people \(2 + 3 * 4) show newline
(= 20, not 14\). Scheme is honest - prefix, unambiguous, mathematical.) show newline
() show newline
