(7. DERIVATION VS. DISCOVERY) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.1 Lamport Time) show newline
(----------------) show newline
() show newline
(In the absence of global clock synchronization, distributed systems) show newline
(establish causal ordering through logical clocks \(Lamport, 1978\). Each) show newline
(node maintains a local counter incremented on message send/receive,) show newline
(establishing a happens-before relation that provides partial ordering) show newline
(without requiring synchronized wall-clock time.) show newline
() show newline
(The happens-before relation was always there--Lamport gave it a name and) show newline
(a notation. That's discovery. Seeing what was already true.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.2 call/cc) show newline
(-----------) show newline
() show newline
(Most language features are about what you can say. call/cc is about what) show newline
(exists.) show newline
() show newline
(call/cc says: the future of the computation is a value you can hold,) show newline
(store, invoke later. Continuations. Time as a first-class object. That's) show newline
(not syntax preference--that's ontology.) show newline
() show newline
(The continuation exists whether you capture it or not--call/cc just lets) show newline
(you name it. The future was always there, implicit in every expression.) show newline
(Scheme made it explicit.) show newline
() show newline
(SICP wasn't about parentheses. It was a course in thinking, disguised as) show newline
(a programming textbook. Streams, lazy evaluation, the environment model,) show newline
(the metacircular evaluator--and then call/cc, which breaks your brain) show newline
(the right way.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.3 The Y Combinator) show newline
(--------------------) show newline
() show newline
(The Y combinator \(Y = λf.\(λx.f\(x x\)\)\(λx.f\(x x\)\)\) is a fixed-point) show newline
(combinator enabling recursion without explicit self-reference. It's) show newline
(elegant. It's also just math that falls out of lambda) show newline
(calculus--derivation, not discovery.) show newline
() show newline
(A certain Silicon Valley venture capital firm took the name as borrowed) show newline
(plumage. Value signaling to people who recognize the symbol but don't) show newline
(work in the calculus. The firm's founder wrote 'On Lisp', evangelized) show newline
(the aesthetic--but Arc didn't have call/cc. Common Lisp doesn't have it.) show newline
(He came from the CL side, where continuations aren't primitive.) show newline
() show newline
(Naming the firm 'Y Combinator' signals: I read the cool parts. Not) show newline
(naming it 'call/cc' signals: I stopped before it got weird.) show newline
() show newline
(The Y combinator is page 300 of SICP. call/cc is the last chapter. Most) show newline
(people don't finish.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.4 The Distinction) show newline
(-------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Derivation: The Y combinator. Recursion falling out of self-application.) show newline
(True but not illuminating.) show newline
() show newline
(Discovery: Lamport clocks. call/cc. Seeing structure that was always) show newline
(there, giving it a name, making it usable.) show newline
() show newline
(Cyberspace is built on discoveries: happens-before for distributed time,) show newline
(continuations for control flow, SPKI for authorization. The derivations) show newline
(are implementation details.) show newline
() show newline
